Parenting is a struggle and it is all about team work. 

As the default parent, I’m the one usually tasked with the repetitive house chores - laundry, folding, coordinating playdates, school pick ups, packing lunch and snacks, weekend activity coordinator, doctor appointments and packing for trips. 

But I’ve been taking more trips out of the city and even the country lately and my partner has figured it out. He may not cut up fruit for the boys for snacks. He may have to cut corners during meal time and get fast food a few nights a week while I’m gone. And lately, he’s been in charge of packing the boys’ stuff for vacation and aside from a few minor hiccups along the way (that’s how we learn), he’s now a perfect packer! 

Some of the stuff, our partners may not do it how we do it but hey they are are doing it. Letting go a little was a little tough for me at first but it’s empowering for my partner and it’s good for my boys to see. It also feels good for me to know that I don’t have to do everything. Other people are more than capable. And now my kids don’t mind blueberry spearmint when we run out of strawberry bubblegum 😜.

Leaving Boston with heart full. 

Life is not a competition. It's about how you can do better by aligning yourself with people who give off great energy, who work hard and know their shit. I went into this prestigious festival as someone who was trying to scrape up a good tape just to get accepted.

When I got accepted, I booked one night at a hotel, just grateful that I got a chance to see what festival life was about. One night led to four nights unexpectedly and then onto the big stage at the iconic Emerson Cutler Majestic Theatre. 

This festival drew in big talent across the nation. Every act was original. I met a host of incredible people who brought their A game and learned so much in just four days. 

In such a competitive environment in a hard and oversaturated industry, one thing stood out for me. No matter what industry, I learned that kindness wins. 

Surround yourself with people who have kind energy. Every little gesture counts. Work hard. Keep at your craft. Make yourself your barometer. Be better each time. You are competing against yourself, not everybody else. People around you will only help you get better. They are not there to take from you. Observing and watching each one slay the stage makes me wanna just get better. Grateful to have had this incredible opportunity.

Humbled and honored to have shared the stage with such hilarious comics @bigjimmccue 
@joelistcomedy @learnmore_jonasi @jlevcomedy @trommertized @rafig213 
and so many others!!

Thank you @bostoncomedyfestival Boston Comedy Festival for this incredible journey, which is the highlight of my career. 

Now back to momlife. 

But first a sugared donut. 

#backtomommymode

Don’t worry people. This was not a true re-enactment. This was me internally talking to myself. 

My mom did tell me though, after I got to the semi-finals, that it was enough days away from my kids and husband and that I need to go back. I was like I know mom. I want to be back but uh, I have just one more thing left to do and that is to perform my best at the Emerson Cutler Majestic Theater with some of the best of the best acts. 

My first time at the Boston Comedy Festival and it was a dream! I met and saw so many incredible acts and Boston comics are definitely one of the best breeds out there. 

But they are not only talented and hilarious, they are kind and down to earth. What an experience to be immersed in four days of comedy and solo time. This experience taught me so many things and also just having a renewed sense of self. I’m always thinking how can I change so people think I’m funnier. Making it through to the finals proved one thing to me, just be yourself. 

Be yourself on stage… and off stage. That authenticity will allow you to shine. 

I didn’t win but I felt like I did. Humbled and so very honored and grateful to the Boston Comedy Festival @bostoncomedyfestival team.

I've always been that "weird" kid. The kid who didn't like to take baths until my sister told me I was starting to stink. I wore dark colors and hated pink. I hated dolls and loved remote controlled cars. I was that kid who wouldn't talk and one day my 4th grade teacher told me that I was a "mute" and that I needed to make friends. I studied 101 dirty jokes in 5th grade so that I could make friends by being "funny". I felt like I had to really work at making people like me because I didn't have pretty clothes or even a straight haircut (oh and being stinky didn't help).

I wore thick glasses and got a bad perm but somehow some boys in 7th grade noticed me - by "noticing me", it meant that I got weird threatening letters snuck into my schoolbag. I was teased and physically bullied by girls and boys. I never told anyone, because I was ashamed. I was called "weird" a lot and I hated it.

Fast tracked to 2020, I did a Zoom comedy show for a school fundraiser. The audience were parents and elementary school aged kids. A 10 year old boy called me weird. When I heard that, I felt like that awkward 10 year old girl again. 

But kids were watching my response. I had to pivot this somehow because I felt like I had a responsibility to any of the kids watching, who may have been feeling like the “10 year old Alyce”. 

So I said said "thank you for noticing! I love being weird b/c it means that you stand out from the rest; and that you have something that makes people curious about you, which  is very special. Soon after I asked “Who else is called weird?" a number of kids raised their hands. I even heard some kids saying "I love being weird”! 

When I'm on stage, I am that same 10 year old girl but this time I'm embracing my "weird" in a cooler outfit. Oh I also take showers daily. Thank you to everyone who came out to the Stand last weekend. It really is the audience that makes the show. Stay cool. Stay weird. 

I'll be in Vancouver, headlining at Yuk Yuks in August and then in LA and I’ll definitely be in pink.

I have a confession. 

On the contrary of what you may think, no I am not a hiker. Some may think but Alyce you look like someone who would love to hike. TBH, my husband asked me what happened? “but YOU used to love hiking!”Nope. Never liked it. But I was in stellar shape pre kids and we used to do a lot of outdoor activities. He thought I loved hiking because I never complained 🤣.

I used to run half marathons, worked out 6 times at the gym, but my activities are different now. I run after my kids, I’ll take them on walks and maybe go to the pool once in a while. But I am not one of those people who want to push themselves physically. I’m just too damn tired now. 

I reminded my hubs: hey man that was pre kids. I’m okay with just trail walking. No need to climb my way to the top of a random rock. Hey, I’m still fun but I know my limits. My body isn’t like it used to be but I can still enjoy a hike. Here’s my gauge: if I can sip coffee while “hiking”, then count me in. If I need two hands for a hike, you can take the kids. 🫠🤪

Anyway for the people here who are dying for my hiking survival tips, here are three must haves: 
1.  a car
2. Coffee 
3. Martha

Our job is to raise kind human beings, who treat others with compassion and respect. 

Here’s a little story. My 6 year old is very selective in what he eats and I make him a smoothie for lunch that has a lot of nutrients since his diet consists mostly of pizza and leftover pizza.

He has been coming home not eating his lunch and after a week or so of that, I asked him why but he was too embarrassed to say. Finally after a while he told me a kid in his class told him that his lunch looked like “throw up”. Let’s call this kid “Duggy” to protect his identity.

My heart sank. I was trying to imagine how he felt at that instant when he heard that about his favorite food. But my kid didn’t do anything to respond. He quietly put his lunch away and just didn’t eat (ahem for a week and a half). But I have to say, I’m glad it wasn’t my kid who made another kid feel like shit. Cuz that pill is harder to swallow. 

This reminded me to always talk to my kids about what’s happening in their world and that they must first and foremost show kindness and respect everyone’s differences even if someone’s lunch looks and smells different from yours. There will be asshole kids but I’m not raising any asshole. 

Anyway, we decided to still invite Duggy to my 6 year old’s birthday party. I’ll just offer Duggy a giant bowl smoothie for his lunch while everyone eats pizza. 

JK. I’m not that immature... or am I?

Yesterday, we said goodbye to our dad, and it’s been an overwhelming mix of emotions. Seeing off my sister at the airport tonight, we felt like Dad would want us to go weird and silly. It’s kinda like trying to find balance in the ups and downs. So, here’s what we did - I could see him smirking. We are wearing his clothes too. 

We love you dad and miss you terribly… ❣️

#grieving

I wanted to express my sincere gratitude for everyone’s heartfelt condolences, sweet messages, and holding our family in your hearts, thoughts and prayers. You have no idea how comforting your kind words have meant to me and my family. 

The hardest part for me was always being so far away from my dad whose health was deteriorating quickly. 

Last Sunday I got the chance to fly back in time to see my dad just a couple days before his birthday. When I got there, the news sounded hopeful. So we planned and talked about what we’d eat on his birthday. He sure loved to eat!

Things took an unexpected turn quickly the next day and he fell unconsciousness. But he hung on in time to ring in his 88th. I was able to spend every day with him until we had to say our goodbyes this past Friday. The goodbye was hard because it felt finite. That is what I’m having trouble processing. But the days I had with him leading up to his passing are a gift and what will keep me going. Every day I am so grateful.

He was a man with few words but had a quirky sense of humor. He was always gentle but a shark of a business man and at Baccarat. He was very stoic but loved when he received affection. He wasn’t always around but made sure he provided for his family. He wore his clothes differently and sometimes sloppy but he appreciated style. 

I would tell my mom, there’s only one of him in a million. She would say “probably one in a billion”. He was different alright - but I see so much of him in me and that makes me kinda proud. I can also squash anyone at baccarat🤭.

Hold your loved ones. Tell them you love them every day. Never delay a call or visit. Don’t get grumpy when your mom or dad calls.

Someone told me that once. Sometimes in the midst of screaming kids, and at the most inconvenient times, he’d call. I would have to make such an effort to pick up with a big excited hello because I never want to regret a moment and because we never know when the last call will be. 

Miss you dad. 

Good night and sweet dreams. I’ll see you at sunrise.

#missingyou #dad

Can we talk about the sandwich generation? For the parents who are in this gap - where we are needed by our kiddos but also needed by our parent(s). The toughest for me was right after my dad’s passing, I had to fly back to my kids who didn’t want to leave my side as they didn’t see me for a week. 

For those who are going through this whether you are taking care of your parent(s) or you have lost them, the pain never goes away. They are part of you. But the legacy lives through you and through your kiddos. 

By the way, Unchained melody by the Righteous Brothers was my dad’s favorite song. He requested it as our Father and Daughter song. I said uh not really appropriate but how about What a Wonderful World? He agreed and I remembered crying through our entire dance. Last year he told me he never liked that song. Oh dad. 🤭

Thank you again for everyone’s kind words. Strangers who don’t know me sending their kindness. Humanity does exist. I love you all. 

#missingyou #funnydad #griefandhumor

Last night marked the 7th day of my dad’s passing. 

It is a belief passed down from Chinese customs that on the 7th day after the passing of the person, they would visit home. My mom prepared my dad’s favorite food and set it out for him on her dining table. 

And I set out to perform my last NYC show of 2023.

I’ve been so distresed that I wasn’t sure that I was going to have the headspace to go out, let alone perform. But I knew I wasn’t going to do any one any good, especially myself, if I held back, stayed home and dwell in anguish and pain. I also felt weird and guilty for laughing and making people laugh while grieving but I now believe so strongly that both grief and laughter and can live side by side.

“Grief... is really just love. It’s all the love you want to give, but cannot. Grief is just love with no place to go.”
― Jamie Anderson

Laughter is a key part of life - it helps us cope with stress, pain and anxiety. And we especially need it when we are faced despair. In fact one of the tasks of grieving is to learn to laugh again.

I am floored by the support and love I received from the show last night - from the beautiful venue and welcoming staff serving up yummy food, the warm and cool audience who even laughed at my most basic jokes to the wonderful line up of comedians who brough their A game, whom I can proudly call my friends. 

I appreciate you all who came out and made it a fantastic show. You have no idea how big of an impact it had on me. I am so grateful to have this community. It really shows that random strangers can make such a huge difference in your life and how kindness and authenticy goes a long way. 

Every one of you injected your own unique magic into the show and I so appreciate you all being such a big part of such a special night: @ralphthemouth81 @ulovelucie @luzmichelleinc @katiecompa @patriciadinglasancomedy @marlarose__ @mochidolci 

Special thanks to the wonderfully sweet and hilarious @sheshedcomedy from San Diego who added the cherry on top. 

I’m glad I didn’t hold back. ❤️

How I WAS doing:
Pic of 9 days ago on day 3 of FLU.

6AM international flight. Attended my dad’s funeral. Planned it all from NYC. Spent QT with mama and waited 4.5 hours at a medical clinic. Almost cancelled shows at the 11th hour. Did three headlining shows back to back in Seattle and Tacoma. 

Swipe to see how I AM doing. 👉🏿

How I AM doing:
Day 12 of the flu. 😷 
5AM flight. Slightly more energy. Still coughing. Less slouching. Grateful. Itching to be back home to squeeze my baby boys. 

I think that’s a definite wrap 2023. And I didn’t break. 😜

#FU2023

Day one of comedy. #EmotionalPurge

Operating at 12% energy. Once on stage, something came over me and gave me the energy to pull through. Human connection y’all. It’s healing I tell you. It was cathartic and an emotional purge. Jaci - thank you for letting me cry on both of your shoulders and Ellen for providing that extra energy to make up for mine. Lin - seeing you there sis, reminded me that we gonna kick ass as usual.

Day 2 of comedy. 
#Ritual 

Raw and rowdy. Crowd was hype. It was a Saturday night crew for sure. I was handing out mango gummies in honor of my dad. HE used to keep them in his pockets and hand them out to friends and strangers and I wanted to start out the show with this ritual. I realized in this moment that my kids are not athletic bc of me. But no one cared bc who doesn’t love candy? 

Day 3 at of comedy. 
#CelebrateLife 

Vibe was fresh and even for a Sunday night, the crowd was full of love and joyful vibes. We cheers to my dad’s 88 wonderful years of life. And it was the playfulness I needed from the crowd. 

I’m not here to tell you to push through when things get tough and you feel like breaking. I’m not a fan of being a martyr.  I’m here to tell you that your mind is fascinating and relentless if you want to do something, you CAN navigate hard stuff. 

And YES, it’s okay to take a step back and take a break when YOU need it. It is also okay to push through on some things that are just not negotiable. Either way, you are remarkable. 

Thanks to my comedy troupe for saying YES to me and being so badass on the stage: @jaciterjcomedy @ellenacuario @lintorious @seattlejuno 

Special thanks to my ride or die friend @flowergurlie 
for always being there for me and my YES girl. 

Seattle & Tacoma thank you for the love. ❤️

This holiday may be tough for some but remember you’re not alone.
 
I think family traditions are important, especially during the holidays. Most traditions are learned in childhood, carried with you and passed on to your loved ones, but I learned recently that you can inherit traditions at any point in life, as I did upon my father’s passing. 

This story about my mom’s traditional Chinese soup is more to me than just a recipe. The way my mom and I bonded over this soup allowed us to laugh and enjoy each other’s company and it was a way to connect back to my dad. I know that sharing this special recipe with my children will deepen our bond and is something I will cherish forever. 

Follow AARP AAPI on Facebook for more stories about family caregiving like mine. Wishing you a happy and healthy new year and enjoy celebrating old and new family traditions!

When I was asked to share a story around the theme of Fire and Ice, I immediately said yes without having an inkling of what I would say. 

I’m a comedian. All my life I have made jokes - most of the time to deflect attention or make everyone feel more at ease. 

But telling a story is a different animal. I decided to take this opportunity to talk about grief. People get scared when they lose a loved one because they think over time, you’d forget about them. I think we need to normalize grief in our conversations; it’s is part of us. Share and talk about your stories through your voice, art, dance, song, even through jokes. 

I learned so much about myself through this journey of grief and I learned even more working with Danielle @danielledardashti - founder of @storyboom.live StoryBoomLive. Thank you and @luzmichelleinc for giving me this chance to tell my story to a room of strangers. I felt so connected and united that night and that’s the magic of story telling... from the heart. 

For the full story, please let me know if you would like to watch it. It is a story about when I was 7 and had a very uncomfortable identity of being Chinese and how one experience helped pivot my perception. 

Thanks for being here IG fam.❤️
